Here are the **key features of ES6 (ECMAScript 2015)** that are most commonly asked in **interviews** and widely used in **modern JavaScript & React applications**.

***

## ✅ Key Features of ES6

***

## 1️⃣ `let` and `const`

Block‑scoped variable declarations (unlike `var`, which is function‑scoped).

```js
let count = 1;
const PI = 3.14;
```

✅ `let` → value can change  
✅ `const` → cannot be reassigned  
✅ Prevents accidental redeclaration

***

## 2️⃣ Arrow Functions

Shorter syntax and **lexical `this` binding**.

```js
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
```

✅ No own `this`  
✅ Cleaner callbacks  
✅ Very common in React

***

## 3️⃣ Template Literals

String interpolation using backticks `` ` ``.

```js
const name = "Raja";
console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
```

✅ Easier multiline strings  
✅ No string concatenation

***

## 4️⃣ Default Parameters

Provides default values to function parameters.

```js
function greet(name = "Guest") {
  return name;
}
```

✅ Avoids undefined checks

***

## 5️⃣ Destructuring Assignment

Extract values from arrays or objects easily.

### Object destructuring

```js
const user = { name: "Raja", age: 30 };
const { name, age } = user;
```

### Array destructuring

```js
const nums = [1, 2];
const [a, b] = nums;
```

✅ Very common in React props & state

***

## 6️⃣ Spread (`...`) and Rest (`...`) Operator

### Spread operator

```js
const arr = [1, 2];
const newArr = [...arr, 3];
```

### Rest operator

```js
function sum(...args) {
  return args.reduce((a, b) => a + b);
}
```

✅ Helps maintain immutability  
✅ Frequently used in Redux / React state

***

## 7️⃣ Classes

Syntactic sugar over prototypes.

```js
class Person {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet() {
    console.log(this.name);
  }
}
```

✅ Cleaner than prototype syntax  
✅ Used in older React class components

***

## 8️⃣ Modules (`import` / `export`)

Supports modular JavaScript.

```js
// export
export const add = (a, b) => a + b;

// import
import { add } from "./math";
```

✅ Code reusability  
✅ Mandatory in modern frontend frameworks

***

## 9️⃣ Promises

Handles asynchronous operations.

```js
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  resolve("Success");
});
```

✅ Avoids callback hell  
✅ Foundation for `async/await`

***

## 🔟 Enhanced Object Literals

Shorter syntax for object creation.

```js
const name = "Raja";

const user = {
  name,
  greet() {
    console.log(name);
  }
};
```

✅ Cleaner and readable code

***

## 1️⃣1️⃣ `for...of` Loop

Iterates over iterable objects.

```js
for (const value of [1, 2, 3]) {
  console.log(value);
}
```

✅ Works with arrays, strings, maps, sets

***

## 1️⃣2️⃣ New Data Structures

Introduced:

*   `Map`
*   `Set`
*   `WeakMap`
*   `WeakSet`

```js
const set = new Set([1, 2, 2]);
```

✅ Prevents duplicates  
✅ Better than plain objects for some use cases

***

## ✅ Interview‑Friendly Summary

> ES6 introduced **block scoping (`let`, `const`), arrow functions, template literals, destructuring, spread/rest operators, classes, modules, promises, and new data structures**, making JavaScript more readable, maintainable, and powerful.

***

## ✅ Most Important ES6 Features for React

✅ Arrow functions  
✅ Destructuring  
✅ Spread operator  
✅ `import` / `export`  
✅ `let` / `const`

